[2
Date: Thu, 21 Oct 1999 09:14:32 -04
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Media reports, Oct 21, 1999

Singapore has no plans to lift a ban on Malaysian pig imports imposed after
a deadly viral outbreak earlier this year, a government statement said on
Thursday. "Although the disease situation in Malaysia has improved, the
Nipah virus is still being detected in pigs in Malaysia," the Primary
Production Department (PPD) said.
Experts were carrying out studies on the control and spread of Nipah virus
disease and the ban would only be reviewed when there was sufficient
scientific information available.
Singapore imposed the ban on March 19 after a viral outbreak in Malaysia,
which led to the death of one abattoir worker in Singapore and more than
100 people in Malaysia. Prior to the ban, Malaysia supplied 800 pigs a
day, or 18% of Singapore's requirements.
--
[The proposed technical name for the pig disease is Porcine Respiratory and
Encephalitis Syndrome (PRES), the proposed common name is Barking Pig
Syndrome (BPS). - Mod.CHC
