[3
Date: Fri, 22 Oct 1999 18:27:28 +0000
From: Jamal Hassan <JAMAL@jphvri.po.my>

Congratulations and well done for your good work thus far. We really
appreciate all your help to us thus far regarding the Nipah outbreak recently.
We are very keen to develop an ELISA to test for IgM antibodies to Nipah
virus in animals. The animals we are interested in are: canine, feline,
goat, horse, mouse,
porcine, rabbit, rat, sheep, and bovine.
This is to establish whether the animals are carrier or at active infection
stage (we had already established IgG assays with the help of Dr John White
of CSIRO, Australia).
However, we are finding quite a problem to find a supplier for IgM
conjugates for the animals. We would be really obliged if anybody who is
interested can contact us over here. It doesn't matter whether the
conjugates are horse radish peroxidae or alkaline phosphatase.
If there is anything we can do for you here in return, please don't
hesitate to drop us a line.
--
Jamal Hassan, Research Officer
Biologics Development
Veterinary Research Institute (VRI)
No 59, Jalan Sultan Azlan Shah
31400 Ipoh
Perak Darul Ridzuan
Malaysia
e-mail: JAMAL@jphvri.po.my
web site: http://agrolink.moa.my/jph/vriph/
[The best assays for IgM antibody are capture assays. That is, one coats
wells with an anti-species (whatever species is being tested) antibody, for
example goat anti-canine. The serum to be tested for IgM antibody is then
added and then, sequentially, Nipah virus antigen (inactivated or otherwise
noninfectious), antibody to Nipah virus (produced in something other than
goat or the species being tested; for example mouse anti-Nipah virus), and
then conjugated anti-species (in this example, anti-mouse) antibody.
Addition of substrate is the final step and we usually use many washes
between additions of each reagent. Thus, if for a capture IgM
enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (MACELISA), one need only have an
anti-species (being tested) antibody. These are what Dr. Hassan needs, not
IgM conjugates. Many are available commercially but some are not readily
available. Tom Ksiazek (CDC) is the likely expert in this area. - Mod.CHC
